Overview

This is a very rough version of a romp through using 1000 genomes data to

Reading the data

This includes data for all 26 populations. What we want to do is to look at two - CHB and TSI. The code below will do that:

pops <- c("CHB","TSI")
dat.spl <- split.vcf(dat.vcf,pops)
dat.spl
## $CHB
## Allelic data frame: 103 individuals
##                     2575 loci
## 
## $TSI
## Allelic data frame: 107 individuals
##                     2575 loci

Cleaning up

There are two things we need to do, having split them up - remove invariant positions from each populations and then remove ones with MAF <0.05. Two TPG functions do that:

dat.spl2 <- lapply(dat.spl,monogon) # remove monomorphic loci
dat.spl2 <- lapply(dat.spl2,setmaf) # remove any with MAF <0.05
dat.spl2
## $CHB
## Allelic data frame: 103 individuals
##                     117 loci
## 
## $TSI
## Allelic data frame: 107 individuals
##                     71 loci

Linkage Disequilibrium

Sometimes at this point, we need to sample from the loci to get a manageable number. However, in this case we dont need to, so well skip the next chunk and set dat.spl2 to dat.smp

dat.smp <-lapply(dat.spl2, function (x) x[,sample(1:ncol(x),100)])
dat.smp

Instead, well proceed and extract the map positions of the selected SNPs from the information from the VCF file:

dat.smp <-dat.spl2
map.n <-lapply(dat.smp, function(x) which(dat.info$ID %in% colnames(x)))
map.p <-lapply(map.n, function (x) dat.info$POS[x])
lapply(map.p,head)
## $CHB
## [1] 50280586 50281168 50281756 50283437 50284377 50285677
## 
## $TSI
## [1] 50281168 50285677 50286953 50289635 50290902 50291617

mamp.p is the critical list - it contains two elements, each a vector containing the map position in base pairs of the snps for the two populations.

Now we apply the LDscan function to the data, which calculates r for each pairwise combination of SNPs.

dat.ld <- lapply(dat.smp,LDscan,quiet=TRUE)

And then we use LDheatmap to make two heatmaps, one of each population.

ldmat <-lapply(dat.ld, as.matrix)
lx <-lapply(c(1:length(ldmat)), function(x) LDheatmap(ldmat[[x]],color=heat.colors(10),title=names(ldmat)[x],genetic.distances = map.p[[x]],text=FALSE,add.map=TRUE))

And we see that LD is much higher in the CHB sample than in the TSI one. Why is that? We will need to explore that further.
